th the exception of racial profiling on our highways and streets, most people favor these methods because they believe they’re a more cost-effective way to fight crime. In Against Prediction, Bernard E. Harcourt challenges this growing reliance on actuarial methods. These prediction tools, he demonstrates, may in fact increase the overall amount of crime in society, depending on the relative responsiveness of the profiled populations to heightened security. They may also aggravate the difficulties that minorities already have obtaining work, education, and a better quality of life—thus perpetuating the pattern of criminal behavior. Ultimately, Harcourt shows how the perceived success of actuarial methods has begun to distort our very conception of just punishment and to obscure alternate visions of social order. In place of the actuarial, he proposes instead a turn to randomization in punishment and policing. The presumption, Harcourt concludes, should be against prediction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCriminal behavior, Prediction ofzUnited States. 0aLaw enforcementzUnited StatesxStatistical methods. 0aRacial profiling in law enforcementzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  alaw enforcement, policing, legal system, surveillance, police, criminalization, racial profiling, systemic racism, race, discrimination, bias, prejudice, trust, authority, government, state power, sentencing, airport security, tsa, prediction, algorithm, actuarial tables, crime, minorities, opportunity, criminal behavior, nonfiction, sociology, political science, criminology, justice, efficiency, statistics, parole, randomization.0 cprintz978022631613040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226315997423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226315997/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles